{"id":"2109.10785","submitter":"Ranyiliu Chen","authors":"Ranyiliu Chen and Benchi Zhao and Xin Wang","title":"Near-term Efficient Quantum Algorithms for Entanglement Analysis","comments":"19 pages, 9 figures, v2 updated results in entanglement detection","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Entanglement plays a crucial role in quantum physics and is the key resource\nin quantum information processing. However, entanglement detection and\nquantification are believed to be hard due to the operational impracticality of\nexisting methods. This work proposes three near-term efficient algorithms\nexploiting the hybrid quantum-classical technique to address this difficulty.\nThe first algorithm finds the Schmidt decomposition--a powerful tool to analyze\nthe properties and structure of entanglement--for bipartite pure states. While\nthe logarithm negativity can be calculated from the Schmidt decomposition, we\npropose the second algorithm to estimate the logarithm negativity for bipartite\npure states, where the width of the parameterized quantum circuits is further\nreduced. Finally, we generalize our framework for mixed states, leading to our\nthird algorithm for entanglement detection, which essentially implements the\nreduction criterion under hypothesis. All three algorithms share a similar\nframework where the optimizations are accomplished by maximizing a cost\nfunction utilizing local parameterized quantum circuits, with better hardware\nefficiency and practicality compared to existing methods. The experimental\nimplementation on Quantum Leaf using the IoP CAS superconducting quantum\nprocessor exhibits the validity and practicality of our methods for analyzing\nand quantifying entanglement on near-term quantum devices.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 22 Sep 2021 15:15:58 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 10 Aug 2022 10:08:46 GMT"}],"update_da